'''Giralia Station''' often referred to as '''Giralia''' is a pastoral lease that operates as a [[sheep station]].

It is located about {{convert|125|km|mi|0}} south of [[Exmouth, Western Australia|Exmouth]] and  {{convert|310|km|mi|0}} north of [[Carnarvon, Western Australia|Carnarvon]] in the [[Gascoyne]] region of [[Western Australia]].<ref name=R2>{{cite web|url=http://www.giraliastation.com.au/#!untitled/c3r5|title=Giralia Homestead|year=2010|accessdate=1 May 2014|publisher=Giralia Station Stay}}</ref>

The homestead is about {{convert|45|km|mi|0}} from the [[North West Coastal Highway]]. The property shares boundaries with [[Marrilla]], Bullara, and [[Yanrey]] Stations, it also has frontage onto [[Exmouth Gulf]].<ref name=R1>{{cite web|url=http://archive.agric.wa.gov.au/objtwr/imported_assets/content/lwe/rpm/catman/62%20part%202.pdf|title=Station Reports|year=1980|accessdate=5 April 2014|publisher=[[Department of Agriculture and Food (Western Australia)|Department of Agriculture]]}}</ref>

The property occupies an area of {{convert|2776|km2|sqmi|0}} of which about half is sand plains and the rest made up of dunes, limestone plains and stony plains all of which are suitable for grazing.<ref name=R1/>

The station was originally established in 1888 the lease encompassed an area of {{convert|2047|km2|sqmi|0}} and was taken up by the H. R. Frencry and Company. Construction of a [[homestead (buildings)|homestead]] commenced in 1910 and was extended to its present size in 1916.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://inherit.stateheritage.wa.gov.au/Public/Inventory/Details/e58c5f13-7d42-42c0-8489-b6f6223c20d2|title=Giralia Station|date=1 March 2012|accessdate=1 May 2014|publisher=[[Heritage Council of Western Australia|Heritage Council]]}}</ref> By 1930 the property was carrying a flock of 44,000 sheep and produced a clip of 700 [[wool bale|bales]] of [[wool]] during shearing.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article74949386 |title=Onslow News. |newspaper=[[The Northern Times]] |location=Carnarvon, Western Australia |date=27 November 1930 |accessdate=8 May 2014 |page=4 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>

Giralia turned to tourist accommodation after being acquired by the [[Department of Conservation and Land Management ]] in 2002 and has been managed as a national park.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.discoveraustralia.com.au/western_australia/giralia.html|title=Giralia Coral Bay Australia|year=2012|accessdate=1 May 2014|publisher=Discover Australia}}</ref> The Blake family remain on the property to run the tourist venue. In 2011, a massive [[bushfire]] that consumed an area of {{convert|1500|km2|sqmi|0}} came to within {{convert|40|m|ft|0}} of the homestead.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://au.news.yahoo.com/a/12461135/nw-station-narrowly-escapes-fire/|title=NW station narrowly escapes fire|author=Tayissa Barone|date=27 December 2011|accessdate=1 May 2014|work=The West Australian|publisher=[[Yahoo7]]|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140502010156/https://au.news.yahoo.com/a/12461135/nw-station-narrowly-escapes-fire/|archivedate=2 May 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>

